DELAWARE LINK VENTURES, LLC
NGPA SECTION 311 STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
1. INTRODUCTION
Delaware Link Ventures, LLC owns and operates an intrastate natural gas pipeline
transmission system, with facilities located wholly within the State of Texas, and is exempt from
the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) under the Natural Gas
Act of 1938 (“NGA”). If by providing transportation services under Section 311 of the Natural Gas
Policy Act of 1978 (“NGPA”) and the regulations thereunder, Transporter’s status as an intrastate
pipeline that is exempt from NGA jurisdiction is impacted, altered, or threatened in any way, by virtue
of any change in statutes, regulations, or other applicable law of any kind, then Transporter reserves
the right to terminate all transportation services under Section 311 of the NGPA and all Service
Agreements and applicable Confirmations related thereto, and to withdraw this Statement of Operating
Conditions, all effective on the Day before any such change in statutes, regulations, or other applicable
law. In light of the foregoing, Transporter presents this Statement of Operating Conditions under which
Transporter will offer NGPA Section 311 transportation service on its system. The rates charged by
Transporter for NGPA Section 311 transportation service shall be established pursuant to 18 C.F.R.
284.123(b)(1)(ii) and such current rates are summarized on Exhibit “D” hereto. As indicated below,
Transporter, in addition to its primary business as an intrastate and NGPA Section 311 provider of
transportation services, also uses its pipeline system in connection with the purchase and sale of natural
gas for its own account as an on system supplier and to maximize the utilization of its pipeline system
(including, but not limited to, utilization of any available unused capacity). Transporter will use its
system to make such purchases and sales and to transport such quantities on either an intrastate or
NGPA Section 311 basis, as set forth herein.
2. DEFINITIONS
Except as otherwise specified, the following terms as used herein and in the Agreement
will be construed to have the following scope and meaning:
(a) “Adequate Assurance of Performance” is defined in Section 5.1.2.
(b) “Btu” means British thermal unit and, where appropriate, the plural thereof.
(c) “Central Clock Time” or “CCT” means Central Standard Time adjusted for
daylight saving time.
(d) “Commencement Date” is defined in Section 11.1.
(e) “Commodity Charge” means a fee assessed per MMBtu of the actual quantity
of Gas, not including Fuel, delivered by Shipper to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) on a given
Day.
(f) “Confirmation” shall be regarded as a single contract, an effective and unexpired
agreement documented by written means, including but not limited to facsimile, e-mail, or other
4
electronic means evidencing an affirmative agreement between Transporter and Shipper on all key
terms and conditions, for a particular arrangement under the Transportation Service Agreement,
including information materially similar to that contained on Exhibit “C.” Shipper’s submission
of a Nomination without an affirmative written agreement by Transporter to all terms of service
shall not constitute a Confirmation.
(g) “Contract Hour” means 9:00 a.m. CCT.
(h) “Day” means the period beginning at 9:00 a.m. CCT on each calendar day and
ending at 9:00 a.m. CCT on the following calendar day.
(i) “Delivery Point” is defined in Section 8.1.
(j) “Effective Date” means the first Day of the term of a Confirmation.
(k) “FERC” is defined in Section 1.
(l) “Firm” or “Firm Service” means the highest level of service, which cannot be
subject to a prior claim by another Shipper or another class of service.
(m) “Force Majeure” is defined in Section 7.2 of Exhibit A, General Terms and
Conditions.
(n) “Fuel” is defined in Section 10.3.
(o) “Gas” means natural gas produced from gas wells, gas produced in association
with oil (casinghead gas), and/or the residue gas resulting from processing casinghead gas and/or
gas well gas.
(p) “Gas Daily Price” means the average daily price of gas at the Waha location as
stated in Gas Daily® (Platts, a division of The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.) in the Daily Price
Survey column, or if such publication is not available, then as stated in another similar publication.
(q) “GPA” means Gas Processors Association.
(r) “General Terms and Conditions” means the General Terms and Conditions
attached hereto as Exhibit A, which constitute a part of Transporter’s Statement of Operating
Conditions.
(s) “Heating Value” means the total gross heating value, expressed in Btu per cubic
foot, at a contract base temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F) and a contract base pressure
of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths (14.73) psi, calculated as prescribed within GPA
Standard 2172 “Calculation of Gross Heating Value, Relative Density, Compressibility and
Theoretical Hydrocarbon Liquid Content for Natural Gas Mixtures for Custody Transfer,” or such
revision thereof in common use. The Heating Value may be adjusted to reflect water content, at
actual measured pressure and temperature.
5
(t) “Impacted Location” is defined in Section 6.4.
(u) “Interruptible” or “Interruptible Service” means Transporter may interrupt,
curtail, or suspend the receipt, transportation or delivery of Gas hereunder at any time and from
time to time for any reason without notice, whether or not caused by an event of Force Majeure,
with Transporter having no liability to Shipper.
(v) “Maximum Daily Contract Quantity” or “MDCQ” means the maximum quantity
of Gas, in MMBtu, exclusive of applicable Fuel, that Shipper may nominate and deliver to
Transporter each Day for Firm or Interruptible Service at Receipt Point(s) or Delivery Point(s) at
a uniform hourly rate over the course of such Day as specified in a Confirmation.
(w) “Maximum Daily Delivery Quantity” or “MDDQ” means the maximum quantity
of Gas, in MMBtu, that Shipper may nominate and receive from Transporter each Day for Firm or
Interruptible Service at specific Delivery Point(s) at a uniform hourly rate over the course of such
Day as specified in a Confirmation.
(x) “Maximum Daily Receipt Quantity” or “MDRQ” means the maximum quantity
of Gas, in MMBtu, exclusive of applicable Fuel, that Shipper may nominate and deliver to
Transporter each Day for Firm or Interruptible Service at specific Receipt Point(s) at a uniform
hourly rate over the course of such Day as specified in a Confirmation.
(y) “Mcf” means one thousand cubic feet.
(z) “Metering Party” is defined in Section 3.1 of Exhibit A, General Terms and
Conditions.
(aa) “MMBtu” means one million Btu.
(bb) “Month” means that period of time beginning at 9:00 a.m. CCT on the first Day
of a calendar month and ending at 9:00 a.m. CCT on the first Day of the following calendar month.
(cc) “Nomination” is defined in Section 9.1.1.
(dd) “Non-Metering Party” is defined in Section 3.1 of Exhibit A, General Terms and
Conditions.
(ee) “OFO Daily Imbalance Fee” is defined in Section 9.5.
(ff) “Operational Flow Order” or “OFO” is defined in Section 9.4.
(gg) “Park and Loan Charge” means fees assessed per MMBtu of the quantity of Gas
loaned or parked on a given Day.
(hh) “Primary Basis” means transportation of quantities from Primary Receipt Point(s)
to Primary Delivery Point(s) up to the Maximum Daily Receipt Quantities and Maximum Daily
Delivery Quantities set forth for such points in Shipper’s Firm Transportation Service Agreement
and, in the aggregate, up to the Maximum Daily Contract Quantity.
6
(ii) “Primary Delivery Point” means those Delivery Point(s) listed in Shipper’s
Confirmation for Firm transportation service as being Primary Delivery Point(s).
(jj) “Primary Receipt Point” means those Receipt Point(s) listed in Shipper’s
Confirmation for Firm transportation service as being Primary Receipt Point(s).
(kk) “Psia” means pounds per square inch absolute.
(ll) “Psig” means pounds per square inch gauge.
(mm) “Quality Specifications” is defined in Section 4.1 of Exhibit A, General Terms and
Conditions.
(nn) “Receipt Point” is defined in Section 8.2.
(oo) “Reservation Charge” means a charge per Day per MMBtu of MDCQ for Firm
Service.
(pp) “Scheduled Quantity” means the quantity of Gas, plus any applicable Fuel,
nominated by Shipper and scheduled and confirmed by Transporter with the upstream and the
downstream pipeline operators subject to any limitations of the MDCQ set forth in the
Confirmation.
(qq) “Secondary Basis” means transportation (1) of quantities to and/or from Primary
Receipt Point(s) and/or Primary Delivery Point(s) above the maximum Firm obligations set forth
for such point(s) in Shipper’s Firm Transportation Service Agreement or (2) to and/or from
Secondary Receipt Point(s) or Secondary Delivery Point(s).
(rr) “Secondary Delivery Point” means those Delivery Point(s) on Transporter’s
system other than those listed as Primary Delivery Point(s) in Shipper’s Confirmation for Firm
transportation service.
(ss) “Secondary Receipt Point” means those Receipt Point(s) on Transporter’s system
other than those listed as Primary Receipt Point(s) in Shipper’s Confirmation for Firm
transportation service.
(tt) “Shipper” means the party that holds all lawful rights and/or title to the Gas that
is being transported and who has a fully executed Transportation Service Agreement and
Confirmation with Transporter.
(uu) “Term” is defined in Section 11.1.
(vv) “Transportation Service Agreement” means the agreement between Transporter
and Shipper whereby Transporter will provide transportation services for Shipper pursuant to the
terms and provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions and any applicable Confirmation.
7
3. REQUEST FOR TRANSPORTATION SERVICE AGREEMENT
3.1 Request for Transportation Service Agreement. A Transportation Service
Agreement is required for all services hereunder and will be subject to all terms and provisions of
this Statement of Operating Conditions and its applicable Confirmation. Any potential Shipper
desiring to obtain services from Transporter must request a Transportation Service Agreement
from Transporter. The request may be in writing, by telephone or electronic medium. Shipper
shall provide documentation to demonstrate its creditworthiness to the satisfaction of Transporter
in accordance with Section 5 hereof.
Requests for a Transportation Service Agreement may be sent to:
Delaware Link Ventures, LLC
Attn: Commercial
2700 Post Oak Blvd., Suite 300
Houston, TX 77056
Tel.: (713) 621-8134
Email: commercial@kinetik.com
3.2 Requirements of Request for Service. Each request for a specific transaction under
an executed Transportation Service Agreement must include the following information:
3.2.1 Shipper’s name, Transportation Service Agreement number and any
applicable individual Confirmation number;
3.2.2 A statement confirming the warranties in Paragraph 4 of the Transportation
Service Agreement are satisfied;
3.2.3 Requested Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) and applicable MDRQ(s)
and MDDQ(s);
3.2.4 Shipper’s requested MDCQ;
3.2.5 The type and character of service requested;
3.2.6 Reservation Charge and Commodity Charge, as applicable, as agreed upon
by Transporter; and
3.2.7 The term of the service requested.
4. PARK AND LOAN SERVICE
Any park and loan service that Transporter agrees to provide to a Shipper will be on an
Interruptible basis and will be performed in accordance with the applicable terms of this Statement
of Operating Conditions, the Transportation Service Agreement, any applicable Confirmation, and
the following:
8
4.1 Parking Service.
4.1.1 A Shipper electing to store (park) Gas to its park account shall submit a
nomination, including quantity of Gas and Receipt Points(s), which
Transporter shall process in accordance with Section 9.1 (Nominations).
The parking of such quantities of Gas shall be for a minimum of one (1)
Day to the next Day. The maximum length of time the Gas may be left in
the park account will be determined by Transporter. All such quantities
of Gas that are approved for parking shall be credited to Shipper’s park
account.
4.1.2 A Shipper electing to withdraw (unpark) Gas from its park account shall
submit a nomination, including quantity of Gas and Delivery Points(s),
which Transporter shall process in accordance with Section 9.1
(Nominations), and which shall be the same point(s) as the Receipt
Point(s) nominated under Section 4.1.1 of this Statement of Operating
Conditions. All such quantities of Gas that are approved for withdrawal
shall be debited from Shipper’s park account.
4.1.3 In the event that the Transportation Service Agreement and applicable
Confirmation have terminated, Transporter may require Shipper to
withdraw all, or any portion, of the Gas quantities parked by
Transporter within thirty (30) Days of Transporter’s notice to Shipper.
If Shipper fails to nominate for the withdrawal of the quantities
specified by Transporter in its notice, Transporter shall take title to that
portion of Shipper’s parking account that Shipper was instructed to
withdraw, free and clear of any adverse claims. Transporter’s notice to
Shipper may be verbal and in such case shall be followed by a written
notice within ten (10) Days.
4.1.4 To protect and/or maintain the operational integrity of its pipeline
system, Transporter may require the withdrawal of Gas in Shipper’s
park account pursuant to the Operational Flow Order provisions in
Section 9.4 below.
4.2 Loaning Service.
4.2.1 A Shipper electing to withdraw (borrow) Gas from its loan account shall
submit a nomination, including quantity of Gas and Delivery Points(s),
which Transporter shall process in accordance with Section 9.1
(Nominations). The withdrawal of such quantities of Gas shall be for a
minimum of one (1) Day to the next Day. The maximum length of time
the Gas may be withdrawn from the loan account will be determined by
Transporter. All such quantities of Gas that are approved for withdrawal
shall be debited from Shipper’s loan account.
9
4.2.2 A Shipper electing to restore (repay) Gas to its loan account shall submit
a nomination, including quantity of Gas and Receipt Points(s), which
Transporter shall process in accordance with Section 9.1 (Nominations),
and which shall be the same point(s) as the Delivery Point(s)
nominated under Section 4.2.1 of this Statement of Operating
Conditions. All such quantities of Gas that are approved for restoring
shall be credited to Shipper’s loan account.
4.2.3 In the event that the Transportation Service Agreement and applicable
Confirmation have terminated, Transporter may require Shipper to repay
all, or any portion of the Gas quantities loaned by Transporter within
thirty (30) Days of Transporter’s notice to Shipper. If Shipper fails to
deliver or cause to be delivered the quantities specified by Transporter in
its notice, Transporter will invoice and Shipper shall pay a fee equalto ten
dollars ($10.00) per MMBtu per Month (or prorated if a partial Month)
until the volumes are repaid. Transporter’s notice to Shipper may be
verbal and in such case shall be followed by a written notice within ten
(10) days.
4.2.4 To protect and/or maintain the operational integrity of its pipeline system,
Transporter may require the repayment of quantities of Gas that have been
loaned pursuant to the Operational Flow Order provisions in Section 9.4
below.
5. CREDIT APPROVAL
5.1 Credit Review. Transporter’s agreement to execute a Transportation Service
Agreement or to engage in a specific transaction under a Transportation Service Agreement is
contingent upon a satisfactory appraisal of Shipper’s or potential Shipper’s credit by Transporter.
If Shipper or potential Shipper has agreed to comply with certain credit provisions as part of a
precedent agreement for a new project, such credit provisions shall govern appraisal of Shipper’s
or potential Shipper’s credit by Transporter for the term of the Firm Transportation Service
Agreement, and satisfactory compliance with such provisions shall be deemed to satisfy the credit
approval required in this Section 5 for the term of the Firm Transportation Service Agreement.
10
5.1.1 If requested by Transporter potential Shipper must provide a copy of its last
two (2) fiscal years of audited financial statements, including balance sheet, income statement,
cash flow statement and accompanying footnotes. If potential Shipper cannot provide the above
information on itself, then potential Shipper must, if applicable, provide that information for its
parent company.
5.1.2 In the event Transporter determines Shipper’s credit to be unsatisfactory in
Transporter’s discretion to be exercised in a not unduly discriminatory manner, at any time during
the term of any Transportation Service Agreement or applicable Confirmation, Transporter may
demand “Adequate Assurance of Performance” which shall mean sufficient security in a form, an
amount and for the term reasonably specified by Transporter. Shipper at its option may provide
one of the following forms of security:
(a) Post an irrevocable standby letter of credit in a form, substance and from a
bank satisfactory to Transporter for services equal to or up to three (3)
Months of all fees and charges that would be due from Shipper if
Transporter were performing such service plus an amount for projected
imbalances, unless a lesser amount is reasonable to and agreed upon by
Transporter based on Shipper’s financial condition; or
(b) Provide a prepayment or a deposit for services equal to or up to three (3)
Months of all fees and charges that would be due from Shipper if
Transporter were performing such service plus an amount for projected
imbalances, unless a lesser amount is reasonable to and agreed upon by
Transporter based on Shipper’s financial condition; or
(c) Provide a guaranty from a guarantor acceptable to Transporter. The demand
for Adequate Assurance of Performance can be satisfied with a guaranty
issued on behalf of Shipper in a format, amount and term acceptable to
Transporter, but only for as long as the credit of Shipper’s guarantor
continues to be acceptable to Transporter, after which time only Adequate
Assurance of Performance in the form of (a) and (b) will be acceptable to
Transporter.
5.1.3 Transporter will not be required to perform or continue to perform service
under any Transportation Service Agreement or any applicable Confirmation in the event: (i)
Shipper has voluntarily filed for bankruptcy protection under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code;
(ii) Shipper is the subject of an involuntary petition of bankruptcy under any chapter of the
Bankruptcy Code, and such involuntary petition has not been settled or otherwise dismissed within
ninety (90) Days of such filing; or (iii) Shipper otherwise becomes insolvent, whether by an
inability to meet its debts as they come due in the ordinary course of business or because its
liabilities exceed its assets on a balance sheet test and/or however such insolvency may otherwise
be evidenced.
11
5.1.4 Should Shipper fail to provide Adequate Assurance of Performance within
two (2) business Days after receipt of written demand for such assurance, then Transporter shall
have the right to suspend performance under any Confirmation until such time as Shipper furnishes
Adequate Assurance of Performance and/or terminate any Transportation Service Agreement or
applicable Confirmation in addition to all other remedies available at law or in equity.
5.2 Right to Reject. Transporter shall have the right to reject any request for
Transportation Service Agreement or Confirmation that does not contain the required information
set forth herein and Transporter will have no liability to Shipper or potential Shipper or any other
entity in connection with such rejection.
5.3 Additional Credit Requirements. In addition to requiring Adequate Assurance of
Performance to secure the Transportation Service Agreement and/or transactions thereunder,
Transporter may require additional or alternate security from Shipper if Transporter’s service to
Shipper is contingent upon Transporter’s construction of facilities. This provision shall also apply
to any assignment of a Transportation Service Agreement that was initially subject to this
provision.
5.4 Transportation Service Agreement Execution. After Transporter has determined
that potential Shipper is creditworthy, Transporter and potential Shipper will enter into a
Transportation Service Agreement, which will incorporate by reference the provisions of this
Statement of Operating Conditions. Multiple transportation arrangements can be agreed to
between the parties and confirmed by Confirmation(s) under a single Transportation Service
Agreement. Neither Transporter nor potential Shipper will have any obligations to one another
until authorized representatives of both Transporter and potential Shipper have executed a
Transportation Service Agreement and have agreed to a Confirmation. Any applicable
Confirmation(s) will contain specific details agreed to by Transporter and potential Shipper for a
particular service arrangement.
6. GENERAL
6.1 Transporter’s Obligations. Transporter will receive Gas up to the Scheduled
Quantity at the Receipt Point(s) as properly nominated and tendered by Shipper under the terms
of this Statement of Operating Conditions, the Transportation Service Agreement, and any
applicable Confirmation, transport and deliver an equivalent quantity of Gas, in MMBtu, to
Shipper at the Delivery Point(s), less Fuel as set forth in the applicable Confirmation.
Transporter’s obligations to receive, transport, and deliver Gas to the Delivery Point(s) shall be in
accordance with the applicable character of service (i.e., Firm or Interruptible), and are subject to:
(i) available capacity, as determined by Transporter, upon its exercise of commercially reasonable
discretion; (ii) an event of Force Majeure; (iii) the existence of a dangerous and/or unsafe
condition, in Transporter’s opinion, due to operations of Shipper or its agents, representatives, or
contractors; (iv) Shipper’s failure or refusal to deliver Gas to or receive Gas from Transporter as
required under this Statement of Operating Conditions, the Transportation Service Agreement, and
any applicable Confirmation; (v) any laws, rules, orders, or requirements of any governmental or
regulatory authorities that limit, prevent, or interfere with Transporter’s performance; and (vi) as
otherwise provided under any other terms and conditions in this Statement of Operating
Conditions, the Transportation Service Agreement, and any applicable Confirmation. Shipper
12
acknowledges that the quantity of Gas physically received or delivered by Transporter may be
different than the Scheduled Quantity and, for those Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) at
which Transporter has operational balancing agreements, the Scheduled Quantity is deemed to
have been received or delivered for the account of Shipper, subject to the remaining terms and
conditions of this Statement of Operating Conditions, the applicable Transportation Service
Agreement, and any applicable Confirmation. In the event of constraints at a Delivery Point(s) or
on a downstream pipeline, Transporter will rely on the downstream party’s allocation at the
affected Delivery Point(s) and, to the extent Shipper’s Nominations are reduced, Shipper will be
deemed to have failed to receive Gas from Transporter as required hereunder.
6.2 Interruption of Service. Transporter will endeavor to advise (by telephone or
electronic medium) Shipper’s dispatcher or authorized representative of an interruption as soon as
practicable, either before or after interruption of service, but Transporter will have no liability for
any failure to give such notice. Transporter will not be liable for any loss or damage to any person
or property caused, in whole or in part, by any interruption of Interruptible Service under any
Transportation Service Agreement or its applicable Confirmation(s). Shipper will indemnify and
hold harmless Transporter, its officers, agents, employees, and contractors from and against any
and all suits, claims, liability, loss, damages, costs (including attorneys’ fees and court costs) or
encumbrances whatsoever brought by any person or entity against Transporter as a result of, or
arising out of, any interruption of Interruptible Service under any Confirmation. Should any third
party with the right to control the Receipt Point(s), Delivery Point(s), or any other facilities needed
for the receipt, transportation, or delivery of Gas hereunder limit or fail to authorize the use of any
such facilities to perform services provided hereunder, Transporter will have no obligation
hereunder to perform any transportation service or receive or deliver Gas hereunder.
6.3 Shipper’s Obligations. Shipper will tender the Scheduled Quantity at the Receipt
Point(s), and accept such Gas, less Fuel, at the Delivery Point(s). Shipper’s obligations set forth
in the preceding sentence are subject to: (i) an event of Force Majeure; (ii) Transporter’s failure or
refusal to receive Gas from or deliver Gas to Shipper as required under this Statement of Operating
Conditions; (iii) any laws, rules, orders, or requirements of any governmental or regulatory
authorities that limit, prevent, or interfere with Shipper’s performance; and (iv) as otherwise
provided under any other terms and conditions in this Statement of Operating Conditions, the
applicable Transportation Service Agreement, or its applicable Confirmation(s).
6.4 Priority of Service and Scheduling. From time to time, Transporter may not have
sufficient capacity available to accommodate all Nominations through specific Receipt Point(s),
specific Delivery Point(s), specific compressor stations, and/or specific segments of Transporter’s
pipeline system (the “Impacted Location”). In such event, Transporter will schedule and perform
service through the Impacted Location in the following order of priority (listed highest to lowest
priority order):
6.4.1 Firm Service on a Primary Basis shall have the highest priority. If there is
capacity available to accommodate some but not all of such Nominations, then Transporter shall
allocate the capacity through the Impacted Location among such Shippers on a pro rata basis such
that each affected Shipper incurs an equal percentage reduction of its transportation rights.
13
6.4.2 Firm Service on a Secondary Basis shall have the next highest priority. If
there is capacity available to accommodate some but not all of such Nominations, then Transporter
shall allocate the capacity through the Impacted Location among such Shippers on a pro rata basis
such that each affected Shipper incurs an equal percentage reduction of its transportation rights.
6.4.3 Interruptible Service shall have the lowest priority. To the extent there is
sufficient capacity to accommodate all Nominations for Firm Service and some, but not all, of the
Nominations for Interruptible Service, capacity through the Impacted Location will be allocated
on the basis of price, but if two or more Interruptible Shippers are paying the same price, then on
a pro rata basis among such Interruptible Shippers. Transporter shall not be liable for any loss or
damage to any person or property caused, in whole or in part, by any interruption or curtailment
of Interruptible Service. Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold harmless Transporter, its officers,
agents, employees, and contractors, from and against any and all suits, claims, liability, loss,
damages, costs (including attorneys’ fees and court costs), or encumbrances whatsoever brought
by any person or entity against Transporter as a result of, or arising out of, any interruption or
curtailment of Interruptible Service.
6.5 Multiple Confirmations. If Shipper has multiple Confirmations, Shipper will not
be permitted to combine services available under such Confirmations. Specifically, Gas will be
received under a particular Confirmation and will be delivered under the same Confirmation.
6.6 Intrastate service. In addition to the services provided hereunder pursuant to NGPA
Section 311, Transporter offers and performs intrastate transportation services that are subject to the
exclusive jurisdiction of the Railroad Commission of Texas, and that are exempt from FERC’s
regulation under the NGPA. To provide Shippers with flexibility to access intrastate and/or interstate
markets, Shippers may contract for both intrastate and NGPA Section 311 service on mutually
agreeable terms, including a limitation that Shipper’s combined usage under the intrastate and NGPA
Section 311 agreements cannot exceed the MDCQ; provided, however, that Transporter’s provision of
NGPA Section 311 service, without undue discrimination, shall not be conditioned on Shipper’s
subscription to Firm intrastate capacity. The description of available intrastate services contained
herein is provided for informational purposes only and shall not be construed to make such intrastate
services subject to FERC regulation.
7. QUANTITY
7.1 Maximum and Minimum Delivery and Receipt Quantities. The maximum quantity
of Gas that Transporter is obligated to receive hereunder at the Receipt Point(s) and deliver
hereunder at the Delivery Point(s) at a uniform hourly rate is based on Shipper’s Scheduled
Quantity, unless otherwise specifically provided in the Confirmation. Transporter has no
obligation to receive, transport, and deliver quantities of Gas hereunder in excess of the Scheduled
Quantity. Transporter has no obligation to receive or deliver Gas in quantities exceeding the
physical capacity of the Delivery Point(s) or Receipt Point(s).
7.2 All Quantities in MMBtu. All quantities of Gas received and delivered under any
Confirmation will be expressed in terms of MMBtu, including, without limitation, calculation of
payments, determination of imbalances, and determination of Fuel.
14
7.3 Adjustment of Maximum Daily Contract Quantity. Transporter reserves the right
to adjust Shipper’s MDCQ if Shipper’s average volume of Gas delivered to Transporter is below
its MDCQ by a defined amount over a defined period of time or waivers thereof as set forth in
Shipper’s Confirmation in a not unduly discriminatory manner.
7.4 Commitment. Transporter and Shipper may agree to commitments, such as a
dedication provision or take or pay commitment, under a Confirmation that would allow Shipper
to commit volumes of Gas up to a certain quantity for transportation on Transporter’s system from
certain Receipt Point(s), with such provisions or waivers thereof to be agreed to by Transporter in
a not unduly discriminatory manner and set forth in the applicable Confirmation.
8. DELIVERY POINT(S) AND RECEIPT POINT(S)
8.1 Delivery Point(s). Transporter will deliver Gas to Shipper, or its agent, under this
Statement of Operating Conditions, the Transportation Service Agreement, and its applicable
Confirmation to the existing points of interconnection between Transporter’s pipeline facilities
and the pipeline or receipt facilities of other parties at the “Delivery Point(s),” as identified in the
Confirmation. Delivery Point(s) may be modified, or additional Delivery Point(s) may be added
to a Confirmation, by mutual agreement of the parties, subject to the availability of capacity.

and adjust its Nominations, deliveries, and receipts to maintain the daily balances between the

make available to Shipper information regarding receipts and deliveries based on the best operating
information available to Transporter and make such information available to all parties to the
transaction. Upon notification, Shipper shall be obligated to adjust receipts and deliveries of Gas
to correct or avoid any imbalance. Any adjustment to receipts and deliveries by Shipper, whether
or not pursuant to notification from Transporter or otherwise, shall be coordinated with
Transporter’s gas dispatchers. Transporter may discount or waive any penalties hereunder on a
non-discriminatory basis.
9.4 Operational Flow Order. If, in Transporter’s discretion, it is necessary or desirable
in order to preserve the overall operational balance or integrity of Transporter’s system,
Transporter may issue an “Operational Flow Order.”
9.4.1 An Operational Flow Order may be issued if Transporter determines that
changes in receipts or deliveries are necessary to maintain overall operational balance of
Transporter’s system or to enable Transporter to provide the services set forth in this Statement of
Operating Conditions, the Transportation Service Agreement and/or its Confirmation. The
Operational Flow Order will identify with specificity the operational problem to be addressed, the
action(s) Shipper must take, the time by which Shipper must take the specified action(s), and the
period during which the Operational Flow Order will be in effect. Transporter will exercise its
reasonable discretion to provide as much prior notice as possible, but not less than four (4) hours
prior to the start of a Day, to Shipper of actions Shipper must take to comply with an Operational
Flow Order; provided that action by Shipper can be required on less than four (4) hours’ notice if
the nature of the Operational Flow Order is due to safety concerns or to protect the integrity of
Transporter’s pipeline system.
9.4.2 An Operational Flow Order may require Shipper to take any of the
following actions or similar actions:
(a) Commence or increase supply inputs into Transporter’s pipeline system at
specific Receipt Point(s), or, alternatively, cease or reduce deliveries from
Transporter’s pipeline system at specific Delivery Point(s), both as directed
by Transporter.
(b) Cease or reduce supply inputs into Transporter’s pipeline system at specific
Receipt Point(s) or, alternatively, commence or increase deliveries of Gas
from Transporter’s pipeline system at specific Delivery Point(s), both as
directed by Transporter.
(c) Eliminate any transportation imbalances, as directed by Transporter.

(d) Conform actual receipts and deliveries to nominated and scheduled receipts
and deliveries.
(e) Delay changes in deliveries up to twenty-four (24) hours to account for the
molecular movement of Gas.
(f) Such other actions that are within Shipper’s control that would tend to
alleviate the operational situation to be addressed.
9.4.3 The OFO Daily Imbalance Fee under Section 9.5 will not apply to Shipper’s
actions taken in compliance with Operational Flow Orders.
9.4.4 Should Shipper fail to adjust its receipts and/or deliveries in compliance

Daily Price plus two dollars ($2.00), or five dollars ($5.00), whichever is greater, for each MMBtu
received or delivered under the Confirmation at the Receipt Point(s) or Delivery Point(s) during
each Day in which deliveries are greater than one hundred and five percent (105%) or less than
ninety-five percent (95%) of the Scheduled Quantities at the Receipt Point(s) for such Day, less
Fuel, while the Operational Flow Order is in effect.
9.4.5 Should Shipper fail to abide by an Operational Flow Order issued pursuant
to Section 9.4, Shipper will also be responsible for any and all damages asserted by any third
parties and will indemnify Transporter against any claims by any third parties resulting from
Shipper’s failure to comply with the Operational Flow Order.
9.5 Operational Flow Order Daily Imbalance Fee. Any variance or imbalance
between the quantity of Gas delivered at the Delivery Point(s) and the quantity of Gas received at
the Receipt Point(s) (less Fuel) during a period when an Operational Flow Order is in effect will
be subject to penalty (the “OFO Daily Imbalance Fee”) as follows:
0% to 3% - No additional charges
3% to 10% - Greater of $1.00/MMBtu or 50% of Gas Daily Price
10% to 20% - Greater of $2.00/MMBtu or 1 times Gas Daily Price
20% to 50% - Greater of $4.00/MMBtu or 2 times Gas Daily Price
Above 50% - Greater of $8.00/MMBtu or 4 times Gas Daily Price

to ninety-five percent (95%) of the average Gas Daily Price for the Month in which such imbalance
occurred. If (i) Transporter transports Shipper’s Gas from a Receipt Point or to a Delivery Point
in which an operational balancing agreement does not exist and (ii) the quantity of Gas actually
delivered for any Month hereunder exceeds the quantity of Gas actually received in such Month,
then any such imbalance may be sold by Transporter to Shipper at a price equal to one hundred
and five percent (105%) of the average Gas Daily Price for the Month in which such imbalance
occurred. Transporter will provide Shipper with an imbalance statement for each Month, setting
18
forth any monthly imbalance and the basis thereof, expressed in MMBtu. Such statement will also
